1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,000
Previously on medium

2
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:02,900
I'm just a girl who wants to be a lawyer.

3
00:00:03,000 --> 00:00:05,900
Wants to do her job,
be a good wife, a good mother.

4
00:00:06,400 --> 00:00:07,800
Be like everybody else.

5
00:00:07,800 --> 00:00:10,500
But you're not like everybody
else and you know that.

6
00:00:11,200 --> 00:00:13,400
Even among the special, you're special.

7
00:00:13,900 --> 00:00:15,700
Who might this be?
Looks familiar.

8
00:00:15,900 --> 00:00:17,800
He and his friend raped a young girl.

9
00:00:17,900 --> 00:00:19,700
Sliced her open.
Took her apart.

10
00:00:19,807 --> 00:00:22,300
Dr. Charles -The Butcher- Walker of Wichita.

11
00:00:22,301 --> 00:00:24,601
Wanted dead or alive
for the maniacal evisceration

12
00:00:24,608 --> 00:00:26,604
of 3 unmarried daughters
from the Great Plains.

13
00:00:26,706 --> 00:00:28,607
Seems like every 15 years or so,

14
00:00:28,609 --> 00:00:30,900
someone hears a voice
and a young girl dies.

15
00:00:33,406 --> 00:00:34,401
Ladies.

16
00:00:34,908 --> 00:00:37,102
If you'd kindly take a seat
in the waiting room,

17
00:00:37,405 --> 00:00:40,400
the doctor and I will finish up
and be with you shortly.

18
00:00:49,205 --> 00:00:51,603
I know it hurts, Maura
but we're almost there.

19
00:00:52,507 --> 00:00:53,801
I'm sure of it.

20
00:00:54,607 --> 00:00:56,501
Our baby is a stubborn one.

21
00:00:56,905 --> 00:00:58,301
Isn't he, Charles?

22
00:00:58,707 --> 00:01:00,901
Takes after his blessed Mother, I suppose.

23
00:01:03,307 --> 00:01:04,901
A word, Mr. Walker.

24
00:01:11,508 --> 00:01:13,702
She's been in labor
for over 30 hours now.

25
00:01:13,806 --> 00:01:15,802
Something clearly is not right.

26
00:01:17,807 --> 00:01:20,501
Just how old is your wife, Mr. Walker?

27
00:01:25,406 --> 00:01:28,503
I think it's time we considered
an alternate method of delivery.

28
00:01:28,508 --> 00:01:29,900
You intend to cut her?

29
00:01:30,007 --> 00:01:33,201
Mr. Walker, I'm seeing an
unusual amount of blood.

30
00:01:33,805 --> 00:01:36,101
I fear it may already be
too late for Mrs. Walker,

31
00:01:36,106 --> 00:01:38,301
but there's still a chance
I can save the baby.

32
00:01:38,308 --> 00:01:39,402
Doctor,

33
00:01:39,406 --> 00:01:41,901
I don't re about the baby.

34
00:01:42,306 --> 00:01:44,503
Honestly, all I care about is Maura.

35
00:01:44,707 --> 00:01:46,402
It's all right, Charles.

36
00:01:46,507 --> 00:01:49,401
The only thing that matters
is our child.

37
00:01:49,608 --> 00:01:52,000
I don't agree.
I don't agree with any of this.

38
00:01:52,108 --> 00:01:53,600
You're going to be fine.

39
00:01:54,606 --> 00:01:57,503
- We just need a little more time.
- With all due respect,

40
00:01:57,708 --> 00:02:00,802
you're not a doctor, you don't
know the first thing about medicine.

41
00:02:01,205 --> 00:02:03,202
There... There is no time.

42
00:02:05,806 --> 00:02:06,901
Maura!

43
00:02:07,105 --> 00:02:08,701
It's all right,
Charles.

44
00:02:09,406 --> 00:02:10,702
Let him do...

45
00:02:10,806 --> 00:02:12,403
what he has to do.

46
00:02:13,006 --> 00:02:14,102
Maura!

47
00:02:17,208 --> 00:02:18,801
Doctor, open the door!

48
00:02:19,608 --> 00:02:21,202
Maura, I'm here.

49
00:02:24,107 --> 00:02:25,103
Maura?

50
00:02:27,907 --> 00:02:28,901
No!

51
00:02:38,807 --> 00:02:40,003
It's a boy.

52
00:02:48,907 --> 00:02:50,601
Sir, your child needs you.

53
00:02:53,307 --> 00:02:55,002
<i>Sir, have you gone mad?</i>

54
00:02:56,307 --> 00:02:58,601
<i>Your place is out here
with this child, not...</i>

55
00:02:58,608 --> 00:03:00,501
<i>not in there with a dead woman!</i>

56
00:03:14,908 --> 00:03:16,900
<i>Sir, what are you doing in there?</i>

57
00:03:18,907 --> 00:03:21,203
<i>I'm going to the police, Mr. Walker.</i>

58
00:03:26,406 --> 00:03:29,502
<i>If you do not unlock this door and
come out here and be with this baby,</i>

59
00:03:29,606 --> 00:03:31,603
<i>I'll be forced to go to the police!</i>

60
00:03:38,108 --> 00:03:39,200
Mommy?

61
00:03:39,806 --> 00:03:41,200
You okay?

62
00:03:44,106 --> 00:03:45,800
Hi, Sugarbear.

63
00:03:47,407 --> 00:03:48,800
Yeah, I'm okay.

64
00:03:49,908 --> 00:03:51,300
Just had a nightmare.

65
00:03:51,505 --> 00:03:52,603
Just a...

66
00:03:53,006 --> 00:03:55,300
a silly little nightmare.

67
00:03:56,105 --> 00:03:57,701
Was it scary?

68
00:03:59,406 --> 00:04:01,003
It was scary.

69
00:04:01,507 --> 00:04:02,703
And sad.

70
00:04:03,608 --> 00:04:05,900
Don't worry, Mommy.
It was just a dream.

71
00:04:06,106 --> 00:04:08,201
You probably won't even
remember it by morning.

72
00:04:10,408 --> 00:04:11,800
Thanks, Bridge.

73
00:04:17,907 --> 00:04:19,501
Think about ice cream.

74
00:04:19,705 --> 00:04:21,503
Or cake. That's what I do.

75
00:04:22,706 --> 00:04:24,502
Chocolate works really good.

76
00:04:24,806 --> 00:04:26,702
- Got it.
- Candy, too.

77
00:04:26,705 --> 00:04:29,101
Or cereal if it's close to morning.

78
00:04:34,208 --> 00:04:36,303
Cookies are really good, too.

79
00:04:40,007 --> 00:04:41,201
Mommy?

80
00:04:41,608 --> 00:04:42,902
I'm hungry.

81
00:04:45,806 --> 00:04:46,903
Never mind.

82
00:05:34,607 --> 00:05:36,803
Hi. I don't know if you remember me.

83
00:05:36,905 --> 00:05:39,401
Allison Dubois.
Of course I remember you.

84
00:05:40,008 --> 00:05:41,700
So you still dream, huh?

85
00:05:42,406 --> 00:05:43,801
That's a good thing,
I suppose.

86
00:05:44,306 --> 00:05:46,801
Better than being like me.
I just don't sleep.

87
00:05:46,908 --> 00:05:48,303
Afraid to, I guess.

88
00:05:48,605 --> 00:05:50,100
Afraid of what I'll see.

89
00:05:50,707 --> 00:05:52,103
There must be a reason

90
00:05:52,207 --> 00:05:54,501
I had a dream about
Walker and his wife, right?

91
00:05:54,907 --> 00:05:57,401
I just don't know how
to make sense of what I saw.

92
00:05:57,807 --> 00:05:59,501
In that case, what do you feel?

93
00:06:00,607 --> 00:06:01,702
Feel?

94
00:06:02,206 --> 00:06:05,801
What you see can sometimes fool you,
but what you feel rarely lets you down.

95
00:06:06,005 --> 00:06:07,003
Well,

96
00:06:07,006 --> 00:06:09,103
I felt the same way I always feel

97
00:06:09,107 --> 00:06:10,801
when I see him in my dreams.

98
00:06:11,006 --> 00:06:13,602
That some girl is poised to die soon.

99
00:06:14,007 --> 00:06:15,701
That  he's up to his old tricks.

100
00:06:15,806 --> 00:06:18,302
That he's found someone
in the here and now to do his bidding,

101
00:06:18,305 --> 00:06:20,201
and it's just a matter of time. 

102
00:06:20,207 --> 00:06:21,801
See that?
You don't even need me.

103
00:06:21,808 --> 00:06:23,400
Then why did I see a moment

104
00:06:23,408 --> 00:06:25,402
from Walker's past,
and not his present?

105
00:06:25,607 --> 00:06:28,603
Why didn't I see the face
of the man he's whispering to?

106
00:06:29,007 --> 00:06:31,103
Or a clue as to who
his next victim's gonna be?

107
00:06:31,206 --> 00:06:33,901
Maybe you don't need
to see those things to stop him.

108
00:06:35,607 --> 00:06:37,300
God doesn't play dice with the universe,

109
00:06:37,405 --> 00:06:40,603
and people like us don't see the
things we do without a reason.

110
00:06:41,005 --> 00:06:42,501
I know it's not easy but--

111
00:06:42,805 --> 00:06:45,802
You  have to have faith that the reason
will make itself known to you,

112
00:06:46,206 --> 00:06:48,303
either in your dreams
or your waking life.

113
00:06:53,208 --> 00:06:55,802
Oh, my poor kids.
I'm a terrible cook.

114
00:06:56,106 --> 00:06:57,702
It smells delicious.

115
00:06:58,007 --> 00:07:00,202
but I couldn't resist.

116
00:07:00,307 --> 00:07:01,800
but  I couldn't resist.

117
00:07:01,905 --> 00:07:04,501
Grocery store up the street
was having a sale.

118
00:07:04,608 --> 00:07:06,703
I've got some extra coupons
if you'r interested.

119
00:07:16,808 --> 00:07:19,901
<i>Nothing like slicing a ripe one
right down the middle.</i>

120
00:07:22,005 --> 00:07:23,902
Sorry, did you say something?

121
00:07:24,507 --> 00:07:26,900
I said the ripe ones
are usually in the middle.

122
00:07:38,106 --> 00:07:40,403
Move your ass, Amanda.

123
00:07:40,706 --> 00:07:42,303
/*Stacey's got a table for us*/ out front,

124
00:07:42,305 --> 00:07:44,101
and I've got a quiz fifth period.

125
00:07:47,007 --> 00:07:48,902
<i>I damn near got a speeding ticket,</i>

126
00:07:48,907 --> 00:07:51,102
but I made it.
Now I don't see you.

127
00:07:51,306 --> 00:07:53,702
Thanks for hurrying over.
Five cars ahead on your left.

128
00:07:53,705 --> 00:07:55,402
I'm in the Volvo.

129
00:08:04,807 --> 00:08:06,602
- So where's the girl?
- She's over there.

130
00:08:06,607 --> 00:08:08,801
She's got the green
school jacket on.

131
00:08:09,506 --> 00:08:11,602
Thought you said
this girl was in danger.

132
00:08:11,706 --> 00:08:12,702
She is.

133
00:08:12,708 --> 00:08:14,402
She just doesn't know it yet.

134
00:08:14,805 --> 00:08:16,402
Do you remember that doctor?

135
00:08:16,408 --> 00:08:18,102
The one who has a thing
for teenage girls?

136
00:08:18,105 --> 00:08:19,501
The one from the 1800s?

137
00:08:20,008 --> 00:08:21,503
Your friend the "ghost guy"?

138
00:08:21,807 --> 00:08:23,601
Don't do that. You were there.

139
00:08:23,908 --> 00:08:25,903
I was there Allison,
and I remember a butcher.

140
00:08:25,905 --> 00:08:28,103
And I remember the girl
he was determined to cut up.

141
00:08:28,108 --> 00:08:29,801
But do I remember Walker?

142
00:08:29,905 --> 00:08:31,802
I can't say I ever really
laid eyes on the guy,

143
00:08:31,907 --> 00:08:34,300
but I'll take your word for it,
so... point him out to me.

144
00:08:34,301 --> 00:08:36,601
Or point out the person
you think he's working through.

145
00:08:36,708 --> 00:08:37,704
I can't.

146
00:08:37,806 --> 00:08:39,807
I haven't got a good look at him yet.

147
00:08:40,109 --> 00:08:41,602
I had a dream.

148
00:08:42,407 --> 00:08:44,502
And I heard Walker's voice
when I was in the store.

149
00:08:44,505 --> 00:08:46,002
He was talking
about her.

150
00:08:46,206 --> 00:08:48,501
So we don't even really know
who we're looking for here?

151
00:08:48,606 --> 00:08:51,502
We don't even know what sack of skin
this ghost might have crawled into.

152
00:08:51,508 --> 00:08:53,602
Assuming he's the one
who's really behind this.

153
00:08:53,808 --> 00:08:55,803
Assuming there's a "this"
he's really behind.

154
00:08:55,906 --> 00:08:58,900
Forget about that. Forget about
who he might be working through.

155
00:08:58,908 --> 00:09:00,503
It doesn't matter.

156
00:09:00,708 --> 00:09:02,902
As long as we don't let
this girl out of our sight,

157
00:09:03,005 --> 00:09:04,202
thing can happen, right?

158
00:09:04,405 --> 00:09:06,803
Allison, you're talking about
round-the-clock surveillance.

159
00:09:06,906 --> 00:09:08,703
Multiple guys working multiple shifts.

160
00:09:08,905 --> 00:09:12,202
and all for a girl, who by the way,
may not even be in any real danger.

161
00:09:15,707 --> 00:09:16,900
All right.

162
00:09:17,708 --> 00:09:19,601
I know a couple of guys
who owe me a few favors.

163
00:09:19,708 --> 00:09:21,403
I'll see what I can cobble together.

164
00:09:22,008 --> 00:09:23,703
<i>I know you guys said
we could only watch</i>

165
00:09:23,708 --> 00:09:25,501
ten hours of television a week,

166
00:09:25,607 --> 00:09:26,802
but Mr. Gressler said

167
00:09:26,805 --> 00:09:30,002
that part of studying current events
is keeping up with the news every night.

168
00:09:30,208 --> 00:09:32,003
You could always try reading the paper.

169
00:09:32,605 --> 00:09:35,203
But the paper's,
like, 60 pages long.

170
00:09:35,306 --> 00:09:38,100
And the good thing about TV news
is that it's only a half hour.

171
00:09:39,906 --> 00:09:42,100
Well, I suppose, if it's for school.

172
00:09:42,308 --> 00:09:44,603
So I can watch
12 1/2 hours a week?

173
00:09:45,106 --> 00:09:46,702
Suddenly she's good at math.

174
00:09:46,808 --> 00:09:47,601
No.

175
00:09:47,605 --> 00:09:49,901
You can watch ten hours of television,

176
00:09:50,008 --> 00:09:52,003
and two and a half hours
of news a week.

177
00:09:57,205 --> 00:09:59,200
That was a scrumptious dinner, darling.

178
00:09:59,406 --> 00:10:01,303
You really should've tried some.

179
00:10:05,008 --> 00:10:06,800
I just keep waiting
for the phone to ring.

180
00:10:06,907 --> 00:10:08,101
I just...

181
00:10:08,308 --> 00:10:10,401
keep wishing I'd seen something useful

182
00:10:10,506 --> 00:10:13,200
like the face of the man
he's gonna use to get to her.

183
00:10:17,107 --> 00:10:18,903
A doctor in Bisbee.

184
00:10:19,108 --> 00:10:20,900
Will wonders never cease?

185
00:10:21,607 --> 00:10:22,901
Dr. Charles Walker.

186
00:10:23,207 --> 00:10:25,000
Pleased to make your
acquaintance Ma'am.

187
00:10:25,007 --> 00:10:25,901
Oh, my!

188
00:10:26,607 --> 00:10:28,102
Listen to that accent.

189
00:10:28,106 --> 00:10:29,702
You sound fancy.

190
00:10:30,207 --> 00:10:32,802
Surprised you'd settle
in a place like this.

191
00:10:33,506 --> 00:10:36,503
Bisbee's kind of out of the way
to have a doctor.

192
00:10:37,205 --> 00:10:38,703
I rather like "out of the way."

193
00:10:38,908 --> 00:10:40,302
And "out of the way" is...

194
00:10:40,507 --> 00:10:43,300
where people tend to need a doctor most.
Don't you think?

195
00:10:45,907 --> 00:10:47,301
You know, my daughter

196
00:10:47,507 --> 00:10:49,200
had some pain of late.

197
00:10:50,208 --> 00:10:51,403
Your daughter?

198
00:10:51,707 --> 00:10:53,202
She's at that age.

199
00:10:53,406 --> 00:10:56,001
Everything's changing,
everything's... hurting.

200
00:10:56,207 --> 00:10:58,101
We got some pills
through the mail, but...

201
00:10:59,205 --> 00:11:01,000
Would you like me to have a look?

202
00:11:02,607 --> 00:11:04,603
Your mother says that you experience

203
00:11:04,707 --> 00:11:06,403
pain from time to time.

204
00:11:08,906 --> 00:11:10,003
Yes, sir.

205
00:11:10,505 --> 00:11:12,402
You ever heard of the expression,

206
00:11:13,108 --> 00:11:14,703
"growing pains"?

207
00:11:15,108 --> 00:11:16,200
Yes, sir.

208
00:11:22,105 --> 00:11:24,300
Would you like me to make them go away?

209
00:11:25,707 --> 00:11:27,900
- Go away forever?
- Yes, sir.

210
00:11:28,706 --> 00:11:30,400
I think I can make that happen.

211
00:11:30,807 --> 00:11:32,603
I think I can do that right now,

212
00:11:33,005 --> 00:11:35,203
with one very simple procedure.

213
00:11:35,608 --> 00:11:36,900
Would you like that?

214
00:11:37,708 --> 00:11:38,701
Yes, sir.

215
00:11:40,408 --> 00:11:41,900
Will it hurt, doctor?

216
00:11:44,008 --> 00:11:45,501
Only at first.

217
00:11:46,007 --> 00:11:47,701
But then you'll feel nothing.

218
00:11:50,207 --> 00:11:51,902
For the rest of your life,

219
00:11:52,608 --> 00:11:54,002
you'll feel nothing.

220
00:12:16,205 --> 00:12:17,403
Amanda?

221
00:12:18,408 --> 00:12:19,901
Are you talking to me?

222
00:12:19,906 --> 00:12:22,103
My name's Allison Dubois,
I'm with the city of Phoenix.

223
00:12:22,105 --> 00:12:24,100
I work for the District Attorney's Office.

224
00:12:24,105 --> 00:12:27,001
Am I in some kind of trouble?
Is this about the car accident?

225
00:12:27,006 --> 00:12:28,703
I don't know anything
about an accident.

226
00:12:28,708 --> 00:12:30,803
- But there is a man...
- <i>Amanda!</i>

227
00:12:34,806 --> 00:12:36,300
Can you hear him?

228
00:12:36,505 --> 00:12:38,003
You can see him!

229
00:12:38,705 --> 00:12:41,203
People actually eat
at this hour in the sun?

230
00:12:41,808 --> 00:12:43,401
Stay where you are!

231
00:12:43,708 --> 00:12:46,700
- Who's this? A friend of your mom's?
- I don't know, she just showed up.

232
00:12:46,808 --> 00:12:48,403
Don't you come near her.

233
00:12:48,505 --> 00:12:50,600
And  stop talking.
We can see you.

234
00:12:51,005 --> 00:12:53,000
Police! I need your help.

235
00:12:53,405 --> 00:12:55,001
He's gonna hurt this girl!

236
00:12:55,007 --> 00:12:57,500
Miss, I think you have me
confused with someone else.

237
00:12:57,607 --> 00:12:59,503
Put her in protective custody!

238
00:12:59,706 --> 00:13:02,601
I know you can't see the man
who's threatening her, but...

239
00:13:02,807 --> 00:13:04,803
Hands in the air!
And body on the ground now!

240
00:13:05,205 --> 00:13:07,801
- He's my friend.
- What the hell is going on?

241
00:13:08,608 --> 00:13:10,302
What's wrong with you people?

242
00:13:10,606 --> 00:13:12,003
You okay, Ma'am?

243
00:13:17,205 --> 00:13:18,300
Actually...

244
00:13:18,705 --> 00:13:21,101
I can't help but kind of wish
he was a ghost.

245
00:13:21,307 --> 00:13:22,400
Excuse me?

246
00:13:23,106 --> 00:13:25,603
Ghosts, for the most part,
have very limited legal rights.

247
00:13:25,605 --> 00:13:28,501
Extremely rare that you hear about one
suing a city or county government

248
00:13:28,506 --> 00:13:30,003
for false arrest.

249
00:13:34,705 --> 00:13:37,003
You were half right.
The guy's name is Walker.

250
00:13:37,806 --> 00:13:39,701
Only it's Jack, not Charles.

251
00:13:40,405 --> 00:13:42,700
Who knows, maybe he's
the son of the son of the son.

252
00:13:43,006 --> 00:13:44,302
I dreamt...

253
00:13:44,408 --> 00:13:46,902
about the birth of his
great-grandfather the other night.

254
00:13:47,205 --> 00:13:49,003
Anyway, this Walker's 36, unmarried,

255
00:13:49,007 --> 00:13:51,601
owns some kind of computer
repair store on the west side.

256
00:13:51,906 --> 00:13:54,403
A DUI 18 months ago,
other than that, he's clean.

