00:27:56,505 --> 00:27:58,200
We drove around forever.

519
00:27:58,705 --> 00:28:00,500
Time was going by.

520
00:28:02,308 --> 00:28:04,503
I realized it had be out for so long.

521
00:28:07,508 --> 00:28:08,703
I needed a drink.

522
00:28:10,405 --> 00:28:11,803
She was too young

523
00:28:11,805 --> 00:28:13,401
to take to a bar, so...

524
00:28:14,906 --> 00:28:17,200
I stopped at a liquor store.

525
00:28:19,906 --> 00:28:21,703
I Got a bottle of whiskey.
Amanda got...

526
00:28:22,308 --> 00:28:23,503
...all excited.

527
00:28:23,607 --> 00:28:26,403
"Let's play a drinking game,
let's play a drinking game."

528
00:28:27,008 --> 00:28:29,900
I didn't want to play a drinking game.
I just wanted a drink.

529
00:28:30,806 --> 00:28:32,701
Well, we ended up parking,

530
00:28:32,906 --> 00:28:34,402
at the high school.

531
00:28:36,506 --> 00:28:37,600
Pathetic, yeah.

532
00:28:39,108 --> 00:28:40,902
She insisted we play this game,

533
00:28:41,208 --> 00:28:42,602
"I never..."

534
00:28:44,606 --> 00:28:46,601
She'd announce something,
something she...

535
00:28:47,005 --> 00:28:49,000
she'd never done,
something she'd never tried.

536
00:28:49,208 --> 00:28:51,403
Something she'd never experienced.

537
00:28:51,907 --> 00:28:53,103
And if...

538
00:28:53,405 --> 00:28:55,302
If I hadn't experienced it either,

539
00:28:56,007 --> 00:28:58,201
then I wouldn't have to take a drink.

540
00:28:59,108 --> 00:29:00,300
I mean...

541
00:29:01,506 --> 00:29:04,300
I walked this earth
twice as long as her.

542
00:29:05,806 --> 00:29:07,900
There's not a lot I haven't experienced.

543
00:29:08,407 --> 00:29:10,001
Suffice to say...

544
00:29:10,805 --> 00:29:12,000
I drank

545
00:29:12,005 --> 00:29:13,900
a prodigious amount of alcohol,

546
00:29:14,007 --> 00:29:15,803
in a fairly short space of time.

547
00:29:18,406 --> 00:29:20,203
Next thing I can remember is

548
00:29:20,407 --> 00:29:22,401
waking up in the car, alone.

549
00:29:31,105 --> 00:29:32,700
I didn't see the blood...

550
00:29:34,006 --> 00:29:35,303
at first.

551
00:29:35,708 --> 00:29:36,900
In the car,

552
00:29:37,006 --> 00:29:38,302
on me.

553
00:29:39,605 --> 00:29:41,201
I didn't see the knife.

554
00:29:41,807 --> 00:29:44,001
Are you suggesting
that you had a blackout?

555
00:29:44,805 --> 00:29:47,003
I'm just telling you
everything I remember.

556
00:29:47,507 --> 00:29:49,402
My client has a history of blackouts.

557
00:29:49,907 --> 00:29:51,600
He's made no secret of that.

558
00:29:51,706 --> 00:29:52,900
For the record,

559
00:29:53,205 --> 00:29:55,000
are you stating that you had

560
00:29:55,008 --> 00:29:56,803
a blackout earlier this evening?

561
00:29:57,007 --> 00:29:59,203
It's certainly happened
in the past, but...

562
00:29:59,507 --> 00:30:00,702
honestly,

563
00:30:01,408 --> 00:30:03,101
I never hurt anyone before.

564
00:30:03,306 --> 00:30:05,903
Mr. Walker, on the off-chance
that you remember a little bit more

565
00:30:05,908 --> 00:30:07,303
than you're... letting on,

566
00:30:07,406 --> 00:30:09,800
I'd like you to know that this
office is inclined to believe

567
00:30:09,807 --> 00:30:12,702
that you suffer from an acute
psychological condition,

568
00:30:13,706 --> 00:30:16,101
and one that, perhaps,

569
00:30:16,908 --> 00:30:19,303
compelled you to do harm to Amanda Peyer.

570
00:30:20,305 --> 00:30:22,402
If you were to make a full confession,

571
00:30:23,006 --> 00:30:25,000
we would take that
into full consideration.

572
00:30:29,105 --> 00:30:31,201
You're quite sure
I did this, aren't you?

573
00:30:36,507 --> 00:30:38,502
- Is there proof?
- Jack, if they did...

574
00:30:38,707 --> 00:30:40,501
you'd be in a cell by now.

575
00:30:42,707 --> 00:30:44,900
The crime scene... is still fresh,

576
00:30:44,907 --> 00:30:47,001
as are the warrants to search your home,

577
00:30:47,207 --> 00:30:49,102
your business, and your car.

578
00:30:49,706 --> 00:30:51,501
The truth is, we're still gathering

579
00:30:51,708 --> 00:30:53,902
enough physical evidence
to formally charge you,

580
00:30:54,008 --> 00:30:57,000
but I'm confident we can do that
in the 72 hours we have.

581
00:30:57,506 --> 00:30:58,802
72 hours?

582
00:30:59,806 --> 00:31:01,503
That's the amount of time
they can hold you in a cell

583
00:31:01,505 --> 00:31:03,200
without charging you.

584
00:31:03,908 --> 00:31:06,003
I can't go without a drink for three days.

585
00:31:06,208 --> 00:31:07,602
Sure you can.

586
00:31:07,907 --> 00:31:10,402
An officer will be in shortly to process you.

587
00:31:18,008 --> 00:31:20,602
<i>A man identified as Jack Walker
was found walking about...</i>

588
00:31:21,507 --> 00:31:23,003
What are you doing up?

589
00:31:23,306 --> 00:31:25,303
Watching you work, on the news.

590
00:31:25,605 --> 00:31:27,903
<i>...and what appears to be the victim's blood,</i>

591
00:31:28,007 --> 00:31:30,803
<i>still visible, on his clothing and face.</i>

592
00:31:34,806 --> 00:31:36,902
He had me completely fooled.

593
00:31:38,505 --> 00:31:39,701
It's okay.

594
00:31:40,205 --> 00:31:41,701
It's not your fault.

595
00:31:42,808 --> 00:31:44,901
You had two days with the guy.

596
00:31:45,408 --> 00:31:47,202
And Walker had a lifetime.

597
00:31:54,408 --> 00:31:56,601
<i>I'm afraid I have, yeah.</i>

598
00:31:57,406 --> 00:31:58,802
I have...

599
00:32:00,108 --> 00:32:02,502
gone into a lover's medicine cabinet

600
00:32:02,805 --> 00:32:05,001
while she lay sleeping

601
00:32:06,006 --> 00:32:07,503
in the other room, yes.

602
00:32:08,005 --> 00:32:09,001
Yes.

603
00:32:09,905 --> 00:32:11,102
It's uncanny.

604
00:32:12,205 --> 00:32:14,702
It's uncanny, how, you know.

605
00:32:16,105 --> 00:32:17,800
Now ask him the other one.

606
00:32:19,106 --> 00:32:20,401
Ask him.

607
00:32:22,908 --> 00:32:24,200
Come on!

608
00:32:25,005 --> 00:32:26,301
You won again.

609
00:32:26,305 --> 00:32:27,501
Come on.

610
00:32:28,107 --> 00:32:29,103
Okay.

611
00:32:29,908 --> 00:32:31,502
I never...

612
00:32:32,507 --> 00:32:33,703
wondered

613
00:32:33,707 --> 00:32:36,202
what it would be like
to slice a girl open.

614
00:32:38,507 --> 00:32:41,603
Touch her blood with my fingertips.

615
00:32:44,106 --> 00:32:45,503
Taste it...

616
00:32:46,306 --> 00:32:48,103
with my tongue.

617
00:32:55,805 --> 00:32:57,603
I do believe...

618
00:32:58,707 --> 00:33:00,401
you're the winner again.

619
00:33:15,307 --> 00:33:16,701
Well done.

620
00:33:17,008 --> 00:33:19,702
And now the moment has come
for me, to thank you

621
00:33:19,907 --> 00:33:21,402
for everything.

622
00:33:23,007 --> 00:33:25,400
You've really been sensational.

623
00:33:25,806 --> 00:33:28,200
Colliding with the car
of a perfect stranger.

624
00:33:28,408 --> 00:33:30,003
Pretending to fall
in love with him.

625
00:33:30,006 --> 00:33:31,700
Calling him incessantly.

626
00:33:32,508 --> 00:33:35,303
You're easily the
most suggestible person

627
00:33:35,507 --> 00:33:37,202
that I've ever encountered.

628
00:33:38,505 --> 00:33:41,701
If only you had the intelligence
necessary to become a physician,

629
00:33:41,906 --> 00:33:44,800
I would happily spend
the next ten, or 15 years,

630
00:33:44,908 --> 00:33:46,702
living inside your brain,

631
00:33:47,107 --> 00:33:48,501
telling you what to do.

632
00:33:49,708 --> 00:33:51,200
But halas...

633
00:33:52,006 --> 00:33:53,601
you have no interest

634
00:33:53,606 --> 00:33:55,102
in the medical arts,

635
00:33:55,308 --> 00:33:57,302
and I have no interest

636
00:33:57,306 --> 00:33:59,802
in influencing the thinking

637
00:34:00,208 --> 00:34:02,103
of a walking Kewpie doll.

638
00:34:03,507 --> 00:34:05,600
So I'm afraid this is...

639
00:34:06,708 --> 00:34:07,903
...good-bye.

640
00:34:08,905 --> 00:34:10,500
Did you bring the knife?

641
00:34:11,505 --> 00:34:12,400
Yeah.

642
00:34:16,407 --> 00:34:17,703
All right, then.

643
00:34:18,606 --> 00:34:20,401
Why don't we begin...

644
00:34:20,806 --> 00:34:23,501
by you stabbing yourself in the stomach?

645
00:34:25,508 --> 00:34:27,402
You don't mind if I watch, do you?

646
00:34:28,606 --> 00:34:29,501
I...

647
00:34:29,708 --> 00:34:32,001
really quite enjoy this kind of thing.

648
00:34:45,206 --> 00:34:46,900
He didn't do it-- she did.

649
00:34:47,608 --> 00:34:50,403
Mr. walker, I apologize you've been
detained the past three days,

650
00:34:50,405 --> 00:34:52,102
but I do have some good news.

651
00:34:52,307 --> 00:34:55,201
Our crime scene unit,
at the insistence of Mrs. Dubois here,

652
00:34:55,207 --> 00:34:57,400
has re-examined all
the evidence in this case

653
00:34:57,407 --> 00:34:59,203
and is saying unequivocally,

654
00:34:59,406 --> 00:35:01,403
that Amanda's wounds
were self-inflicted.

655
00:35:07,406 --> 00:35:08,701
Again...

656
00:35:09,408 --> 00:35:10,801
I apologize.

657
00:35:11,908 --> 00:35:12,902
My God.

658
00:35:12,908 --> 00:35:14,602
No apology is necessary.

659
00:35:15,706 --> 00:35:17,802
Under the circumstances, I just--

660
00:35:17,908 --> 00:35:19,600
Go home.
Get some rest.

661
00:35:19,607 --> 00:35:22,001
My office will be speaking
with your attorney.

662
00:35:22,208 --> 00:35:24,002
There may still be some civil issues

663
00:35:24,005 --> 00:35:25,800
that Amanda's parents want to litigate.

664
00:35:25,808 --> 00:35:28,102
having to do with
offering alcohol to a minor,

665
00:35:28,106 --> 00:35:29,403
but I do believe

666
00:35:29,405 --> 00:35:31,602
for the most part,
you're out of the woods.

667
00:35:32,805 --> 00:35:35,300
I have no idea what you did,
but thank you.

668
00:35:36,305 --> 00:35:37,702
How are you feeling?

669
00:35:38,406 --> 00:35:40,203
Other than being in shock, uh...

670
00:35:40,508 --> 00:35:41,501
good.

671
00:35:41,807 --> 00:35:44,303
The first two days
without alcohol were difficult.

672
00:35:45,105 --> 00:35:46,301
Today...

673
00:35:48,105 --> 00:35:49,403
Who knows?

674
00:35:49,608 --> 00:35:52,301
I might actually make a habit
of this... not-drinking thing.

675
00:35:54,907 --> 00:35:56,502
Can I talk to you?

676
00:35:57,908 --> 00:35:59,403
What is it? I'm busy.

677
00:35:59,708 --> 00:36:01,002
What are you doing?

678
00:36:01,305 --> 00:36:02,901
I'm reading the news.

679
00:36:04,405 --> 00:36:06,102
But I don't understand.

680
00:36:06,308 --> 00:36:07,901
Why would you <i>read</i> the news

681
00:36:07,908 --> 00:36:09,800
while you could watch it on TV?

682
00:36:13,307 --> 00:36:14,700
Got it!
Hello?

683
00:36:15,107 --> 00:36:16,403
Mrs. Dubois?

684
00:36:16,907 --> 00:36:18,401
Jack, is that you?

685
00:36:18,708 --> 00:36:20,103
Are you drinking?

686
00:36:20,508 --> 00:36:22,803
No. God knows I want to.

687
00:36:23,707 --> 00:36:25,900
- Where are you?
- I'm at the shop.

688
00:36:25,906 --> 00:36:28,200
I keep thinking I should go out.

689
00:36:28,407 --> 00:36:30,701
I kinda want to be around
some young people.

690
00:36:30,707 --> 00:36:32,000
- Girls.
- Listen to me.

691
00:36:32,007 --> 00:36:34,002
Stay right where you are.
Don't go anywhere.

692
00:36:34,006 --> 00:36:35,500
I'll be there quick as I can.

693
00:36:49,307 --> 00:36:50,401
Jack!

694
00:36:52,605 --> 00:36:54,201
Jack, are you here?

695
00:36:55,107 --> 00:36:56,002
Jack!

696
00:36:56,308 --> 00:36:57,702
Are you here?

697
00:37:05,007 --> 00:37:07,503
Lovely to see you.
I do so appreciate the way

698
00:37:07,605 --> 00:37:09,501
you ran right over here
when I called.

699
00:37:10,006 --> 00:37:11,601
The good doctor, I presume.

700
00:37:11,905 --> 00:37:13,600
Well, maybe not so good.

701
00:37:13,805 --> 00:37:15,803
Maybe not really a doctor either.

702
00:37:17,105 --> 00:37:19,001
So how long
has it been you and not him?

703
00:37:19,406 --> 00:37:20,802
In the jail?

704
00:37:21,007 --> 00:37:23,000
In the interrogation room
with the lawyer?

705
00:37:23,707 --> 00:37:25,302
What about the night Amanda died?

706
00:37:25,806 --> 00:37:27,200
Oh please, I'm good.

707
00:37:27,508 --> 00:37:28,900
But not that good.

708
00:37:29,506 --> 00:37:31,400
I've really only just begun

709
00:37:31,407 --> 00:37:34,202
my residency inside young Jack's skin.

710
00:37:36,006 --> 00:37:37,702
What a superb fit.

711
00:37:38,705 --> 00:37:42,102
Like a suit that's been
custom-made for me by God.

712
00:37:45,206 --> 00:37:47,000
I'll always be grateful for your help.

713
00:37:47,007 --> 00:37:48,301
My help?

714
00:37:48,305 --> 00:37:50,400
Oh my, yes.
I couldn't have done it without you.

715
00:37:50,707 --> 00:37:53,802
I've been whispering
in that boy's ear for 20 years,

716
00:37:54,007 --> 00:37:55,600
trying to pierce that...

717
00:37:55,807 --> 00:37:58,803
self-imposed haze of alcohol.

718
00:37:59,505 --> 00:38:01,803
I tried tempting him with that girl,

719
00:38:01,806 --> 00:38:04,202
but apparently he's managed
to rot his libido

720
00:38:04,305 --> 00:38:05,901
as well as his liver.

721
00:38:06,406 --> 00:38:08,101
And then, suddenly,

722
00:38:08,906 --> 00:38:10,602
there you were...

723
00:38:11,107 --> 00:38:12,100
screaming

724
00:38:12,206 --> 00:38:14,401
for the police in that
supermarket parking lot,

725
00:38:14,508 --> 00:38:16,003
and I thought,
"Wait a second.

726
00:38:16,105 --> 00:38:17,703
"Your good friend Allison,

727
00:38:17,806 --> 00:38:19,601
"she's just presented you with...

728
00:38:19,705 --> 00:38:21,403
a much better idea!"

729
00:38:21,506 --> 00:38:22,503
Me?

730
00:38:22,605 --> 00:38:24,501
Well, thanks to that scene that you made,

731
00:38:24,507 --> 00:38:26,800
my drunken, impotent relative

732
00:38:27,007 --> 00:38:29,902
now had the attention
of the local authorities.

733
00:38:31,805 --> 00:38:35,001
If something unfortunate
were to happen to young Amanda,

734
00:38:35,208 --> 00:38:36,101
well,

735
00:38:36,108 --> 00:38:38,402
he'd be the first person they'd lock up.

736
00:38:39,005 --> 00:38:41,701
A man can get
awfully thirsty in a jail cell.

737
00:38:41,807 --> 00:38:43,501
Awfully thirsty.

738
00:38:44,005 --> 00:38:45,902
And awfully clear-headed.

739
00:38:46,608 --> 00:38:50,100
I knew for the first time
in nearly 20 years,

740
00:38:50,807 --> 00:38:52,502
he'd finally hear me.

741
00:38:52,806 --> 00:38:54,203
And here we are.

742
00:38:54,506 --> 00:38:57,501
You did all of that
so you could finally be in the skin

743
00:38:57,607 --> 00:38:59,702
of someone who looked
exactly like you did?

744
00:38:59,908 --> 00:39:01,701
when you ravaged teenage girls?

745
00:39:02,805 --> 00:39:03,803
Allison.

746
00:39:04,205 --> 00:39:06,102
I did all that so I could
be inside the skin

747
00:39:06,205 --> 00:39:08,102
of someone who looked like me...

748
00:39:10,108 --> 00:39:11,702
when I ravaged you.

749
00:39:16,308 --> 00:39:17,802
I know what you're thinking.

750
00:39:17,906 --> 00:39:19,300
Where's the scalpel?

751
00:39:19,308 --> 00:39:21,002
Where's the surgical saw?

752
00:39:21,108 --> 00:39:22,303
Help!

753
00:39:22,406 --> 00:39:25,600
One of my great disappointments
as I spend time with my progeny,

754
00:39:26,806 --> 00:39:28,501
is their compete and utter

755
00:39:28,507 --> 00:39:30,501
lack of interest in the medical arts.

756
00:39:31,308 --> 00:39:32,402
Oh, well!

757
00:39:32,408 --> 00:39:34,703
What's a great-great grandfather to do?

758
00:39:35,107 --> 00:39:36,403
Adapt, I say.

759
00:39:39,106 --> 00:39:40,203
And so,

760
00:39:40,307 --> 00:39:42,101
in a one-time-only performance,

761
00:39:42,108 --> 00:39:44,301
tonight's slaying will be performed

762
00:39:44,305 --> 00:39:45,601
bare-handed!

763
00:39:45,608 --> 00:39:48,903
I know you're flattered, Allison.
Try not to get too choked up.

764
00:40:03,408 --> 00:40:05,401
If all you wanted to do was kill me,

765
00:40:05,406 --> 00:40:07,400
why did you send me
all of those dreams?

766
00:40:10,606 --> 00:40:12,001
You didn't.

767
00:40:12,405 --> 00:40:14,201
Did you?
She did.

768
00:40:14,808 --> 00:40:16,100
To stop you.

769
00:40:16,206 --> 00:40:17,901
You know nothing of Maura.

770
00:40:18,006 --> 00:40:19,100
I do!

771
00:40:19,706 --> 00:40:21,202
She's here!

772
00:40:21,505 --> 00:40:23,601
She never stopped watching you.

773
00:40:23,808 --> 00:40:25,600
She sees you even now.

774
00:40:26,008 --> 00:40:27,703
What you're doing to me.

775
00:40:28,206 --> 00:40:30,902
What you're doing to her
great-great grandson.

776
00:40:31,607 --> 00:40:33,101
If you kill me,

777
00:40:33,308 --> 00:40:36,303
Jack is going to spend
the rest of his life in prison.

778
00:40:36,808 --> 00:40:38,401
and do you honestly think

779
00:40:38,505 --> 00:40:41,903
she loves him any less
than the child she died for?

780
00:41:22,905 --> 00:41:24,401
<i>Oh, my God.</i>

781
00:41:29,006 --> 00:41:30,702
What am I doing here?

782
00:41:35,005 --> 00:41:36,700
<i>What are ghosts really?</i>

783
00:41:36,907 --> 00:41:38,200
They're energy.

784
00:41:38,406 --> 00:41:40,101
The energy we leave behind.

785
00:41:40,406 --> 00:41:41,803
And energy is power.

786
00:41:42,605 --> 00:41:45,000
<i>Who knows what might happen
when a spirit as powerful</i>

787
00:41:45,007 --> 00:41:47,901
as Charles Walker's finally
decides to cross over?

788
00:41:48,306 --> 00:41:51,403
Or what would happen if the other side
just decided to take him?

